<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911127-0123</DOCNO><DOCID>911127-0123.</DOCID><HL>   Union Pacific Says   Half of Its Crews   Agree to Reduction   ----   By Daniel Machalaba   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>11/27/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><CO>   LABOR UNP</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>RAILROADS (RAI)</IN><NS>LABOR, UNIONS, STRIKES, WAGES, RECRUITMENT (LAB)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   OMAHA, Neb. -- Union Pacific Railroad Co. said about halfof its train crew employees represented by the UnitedTransportation Union ratified agreements to cut train crewsizes.   Union Pacific Railroad, a unit of Union Pacific Corp. ofBethlehem, Pa., said it has similar agreements awaitingratification votes on the rest of its 19,000-mile system. Thecompany said it has applied to the National Mediation Boardfor binding arbitration to provide agreements by Dec. 31 ifratification efforts are unsuccessful.</LP><TEXT>   The agreements represent the latest major crew reductionsto be negotiated since a special board appointed by Congressmade its final rail labor recommendations last summer.Burlington Northern Inc. and Norfolk Southern Corp. employeeshave agreed to crew reductions.   The Union Pacific agreements call for elimination ofbrakemen on all direct freight trains which do a minimum ofswitching of cars during trips. Currently, most Union Pacificfreight trains carry one or more brakemen in addition to theconductor and engineer.   Redundant train crew members on the Union Pacific Railroadwill be offered a choice of taking a separation payment orremaining in reserve status. A Union Pacific spokesmandeclined to provide details other than to say that theagreements follow the pattern set by other railroads.   Other rail carriers have offered their surplus crewmembers a choice of taking one-time separation paymentsranging from $50,000 to $60,000 or remaining in reservestatus at about 75% of their pay.   Union Pacific officials said they expect traffic growth toeventually create work opportunities for surplus train crewmembers who elect to go on the reserve board. They haveestimated that about 4,000 of their train crew members aresurplus at present traffic levels.   &quot;We want to keep our surplus people, anticipating thatincreased business will put them back on new trains,&quot; saidTom Watts, Union Pacific Railroad's vice president of laborrelations. Mr. Watts said the railroad expects a 25% increasein traffic over the next five years.</TEXT></DOC>